Genomic Rearrangement, Copy Number Alteration, and Mutual Exclusivity

sho

2020 7 24

I. Overview

1. Load libraries and Data (via cBio Portal CGDSR)

1-1. Install Rtools (for compiling R packages from source)

First, install Rtools from binary. The link is as follows; https://cran.r-project.org/bin/windows/Rtools/.

After installing Rtools, type the following into the R console in order to associate PATH variables to the simulated R-bash environments executable binaries, such as make.

I downgraded from rtool40 to rtools35 because R itself downgraded from 4.0.2 to 3.6.3 for compatibility with DISCOVER package, which is not yet released for versions 4.0.0 or higher.

writeLines('PATH="C:\\rtools35\\usr\\bin;${PATH}"', con="~/.Renviron")
Sys.which("make")
##            make 
## "/usr/bin/make"

1-2. Install discover package/dependencies and other required tools.

We need following libraries: - discover: DISCOVER is a tool for calculating co-occurrences and mutual exclusivity, as described in A novel independence test for somatic alterations in cancer shows that biology drives mutual exclusivity but chance explains co-occurrence. - cgdsr: This is an R-based API(application programming interface) for downloading and processing the right data from CGDS (Cancer Genomics Data Server). https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/cgdsr/index.html - maftools: Summarize, Analyze and Visualize MAF Files and get insight into the somatic variants https://www.bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/vignettes/maftools/inst/doc/maftools.html - cometExactTest(Exact Test from the Combinations of Mutually Exclusive Alterations): Statistical algorithm for identifying combinations of mutually exclusive alterations in cancer genomes. https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/cometExactTest/index.html

Theres no DISCOVER package for R4.0.0 or up. Therefore it seems that I have to resort to downgrading or install separate version of R 3.6.~.

options(repos=c(getOption("repos"), "http://ccb.nki.nl/software/discover/repos/r"))
install.packages("discover")

Theres also option of installing package from locally downloaded source file.

Then I installed cgdsr package.

In order to install maftools and cometExactTest, I need BiocManager.

1-3. Load libraries

library(discover)
## Loading required package: matrixStats
library(cgdsr)
## Please send questions to cbioportal@googlegroups.com
library(maftools)
## 
## Attaching package: 'maftools'
## The following object is masked from 'package:cgdsr':
## 
##     getClinicalData
library(cometExactTest)

2. Form Binary Mutation Matrix from Somatic Mutation and CNA data from cBio Portal CGDSR

## 262                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     The Angiosarcoma Project is an ongoing patient-driven initiative. This archived Angiosarcoma Project dataset was analyzed in the linked Nature Medicine 2020 manuscript, and is derived from 48 samples from 36 angiosarcoma patients. Angiosarcoma tumor specimens (FFPE) were subjected to whole-exome sequencing (along with matched germline whole-exome sequencing). In addition to genomic data, this study includes patient-reported data (pre-pended as PRD), medical record data (MedR), and pathology report data (PATH). All annotations have been de-identified. Questions about these data can be directed to data@ascproject.org.
## 263                                                                                  The Metastatic Breast Cancer Project (www.mbcproject.org) is an ongoing patient-driven initiative. This dataset release is derived from 237 samples, including both primary and/or metastatic tumor specimens (FFPE) from 180 patients who developed metastatic breast cancer. 237 samples have undergone whole-exome sequencing (along with matched germline whole-exome sequencing) and 146 of those samples have also undergone RNA-sequencing. This study includes genomic data, patient-reported data (prepended as PRD), medical record data (MedR), and pathology report data (PATH). All annotations have been de-identified. As these data were generated in a research laboratory, not a clinical laboratory, they are for research purposes only and cannot be used to inform clinical decision-making. For questions about these data, including how to cite, please visit www.mbcproject.org/data-release or direct questions to data@mbcproject.org.
## 264                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          The Metastatic Prostate Cancer Project is a patient-driven initiative. This study includes genomic data, cfDNA tumor fractions, patient-reported data (pre-pended as PRD), medical record data (MedR), and pathology report data (PATH).  As these data were generated in a research, not a clinical, laboratory, they are for research purposes only and cannot be used to inform clinical decision-making. All annotations have been de-identified. More information is available at www.mpcproject.org. For questions about these data, including how to cite, please visit www.mpcproject.org/data-release or direct questions to data@mpcproject.org.

getCancerStudies(cbiop)$description
##   [1] "Whole exome sequencing of 23 surgically resected pancreatic carcinomas with acinar differentiation and their matched normals."                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          
##   [2] "Whole exome sequencing and transcriptome analysis of 34 Acral Melanoma patients (33 with matched normals)."                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             
##   [3] "Comprehensive profiling of infant MLL-rearranged acute lymphoblastic leukemia (MLL-R ALL)"                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              
##   [4] "Whole-genome and/or whole-exome sequencing of ERG-altered B-ALL tumor/normal pairs."                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    
##   [5] "Whole-exome sequencing of 672 acute myeloid leukemia samples (with 454 matched normals) from the Beat AML program."                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     
##   [6] "TCGA Acute Myeloid Leukemia; raw data at the <A HREF=\"https://tcga-data.nci.nih.gov/\">NCI</A>; source mutation data from <a HREF=\"http://gdac.broadinstitute.org/runs/stddata__2016_01_28/data/LAML/20160128/gdac.broadinstitute.org_LAML.Mutation_Packager_Calls.Level_3.2016012800.0.0.tar.gz\">GDAC Firehose</A>."                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                
##   [7] "Whole-genome or whole-exome sequencing analysis of 200 adult de novo AML tumor/normal pairs. ## [262] "The Angiosarcoma Project is an ongoing patient-driven initiative. This archived Angiosarcoma Project dataset was analyzed in the linked Nature Medicine 2020 manuscript, and is derived from 48 samples from 36 angiosarcoma patients. Angiosarcoma tumor specimens (FFPE) were subjected to whole-exome sequencing (along with matched germline whole-exome sequencing). In addition to genomic data, this study includes patient-reported data (pre-pended as PRD), medical record data (MedR), and pathology report data (PATH). All annotations have been de-identified. Questions about these data can be directed to data@ascproject.org."                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        
## [263] "The Metastatic Breast Cancer Project (www.mbcproject.org) is an ongoing patient-driven initiative. This dataset release is derived from 237 samples, including both primary and/or metastatic tumor specimens (FFPE) from 180 patients who developed metastatic breast cancer. 237 samples have undergone whole-exome sequencing (along with matched germline whole-exome sequencing) and 146 of those samples have also undergone RNA-sequencing. This study includes genomic data, patient-reported data (prepended as PRD), medical record data (MedR), and pathology report data (PATH). All annotations have been de-identified. As these data were generated in a research laboratory, not a clinical laboratory, they are for research purposes only and cannot be used to inform clinical decision-making. For questions about these data, including how to cite, please visit www.mbcproject.org/data-release or direct questions to data@mbcproject.org."

2-6. Somatic Mutation Data and CNV Data Loading

somatic <- getMutationData(cbiop, cases, variable1, as.list(d_gene)$V1)
cnv <- getProfileData(cbiop, as.list(d_gene)$V1, variable2, cases)

2-7. Building a Binary Mutation Matrix

1 - mutation / 0 - Wildtype

If CNV goes higher than 0.1, CNV is considered +1, and if CNV is less than -0.1, its considered -1. And if in between, CNV is considered 0.

# Copy Number Processing

na.omit_cnv <- na.omit(cnv)
for (j in 1:ncol(na.omit_cnv)){
  for (i in 1:nrow(na.omit_cnv)){
    if (na.omit_cnv[i,j] >= 0.1){
      na.omit_cnv[i,j] <- 1
    }
    else if (na.omit_cnv[i,j] <= -0.1){
      na.omit_cnv[i,j] <- -1
    }
    else {
      na.omit_cnv[i, j] <- 0
    }
  }
}
patient <- rownames(cnv) # patient ID only
gene <- colnames(cnv) # gene name only
somatic$case_id <- gsub("-", ".", somatic$case_id) # replacing "-" to "." to make the format equivalent
# between `cnv` and `somatic`
# Binary Matrix
bm_laml <- data.frame(patient) #binary matrix of laml
colnames(bm_laml) <- c("pat")
for (g in 1:length(gene)){
  som_sel <- subset(somatic, somatic$gene_symbol==gene[g])$case_id 
  # case IDs for cases that show somatic mutations at certain gene.
  cnv_sel <- rownames(na.omit_cnv[,g]!=0,) #g-th column (of a gene) = CNV status of that gene.
  # cnv_sel selects for patient IDs that have CNVs at certain gene.
  pat <- unique(c(som_sel, cnv_sel))
  tmp <- data.frame(pat, 1)
  colnames(tmp) <- c("pat", gene[g])
  bm_laml <- merge(bm_laml, tmp, by=c("pat"), all.x=T)
}

Change all bm_laml values that are NA to zero.

bm_laml[is.na(bm_laml)] <- 0

II. Mutual Exclusivity Analysis and Coverage with DISCOVER

In this practice, we use TCGA breast cancer patients somatic mutation profile data. This little practice session seems to be based on this document right here. Its called An Introduction to DISCOVER.

1. Load library and data

Load discover library and also load BRCA.mut data.

library(discover)

2. Pass the mutation matrix to discover.matrix object for estimation of a background matrix.

Generate the background mutation matrix. An important ingredient of the DISCOVER test is the estimation of a background matrix. This is how tumour-specific alteration rates can be used by the test. To estimate this background matrix, a discover.matrix object is created and passed the mutation matrix. Depending on the size of the matrix this might take some time. This estimation step only needs to be performed once.

events <- discover.matrix(BRCA.mut)

Note that for estimating this background matrix, it is important that the full mutation matrix is provided. Even if only a subset of genes will subsequently be used in the analysis, a whole-genome view of the mutations is required for this first step. Indeed, for this example we will only look for mutual exclusivity between genes that are mutated in at least 25 tumours.

L-BFGS-B algorithm is a machine learning algorithm that learns how to classify if there are groups that exclude each other or not.

subset <- rowSums(BRCA.mut) > 25 # shows which genes have
# mutations in more than 25 samples.
head(subset, 20)
##     A1CF      A2M    A2ML1   A4GALT    A4GNT     AAAS     AACS    AADAC 
##    FALSE    FALSE    FALSE    FALSE    FALSE    FALSE    FALSE    FALSE 
##  AADACL2  AADACL4    AADAT    AAGAB     AAK1    AANAT     AARS    AARS2 
##    FALSE    FALSE    FALSE    FALSE    FALSE    FALSE    FALSE    FALSE 
##   AARSD1    AASDH AASDHPPT     AASS 
##    FALSE    FALSE    FALSE    FALSE

3. Pairwise tests

We can now test for mutual exclusivity between all pairs of genes using the pairwise.discover.test function. Its only required argument is an instance of the discover.matrix class like we created above. In order to only analyse frequently mutated genes, we select the corresponding rows before passing the matrix to the function. Again, depending on the size of the matrix, this function might take some time.

result.mutex <- pairwise.discover.test(events[subset, ])
# Corresponding rows according to subset is selected in events

We can get a quick overview of the results of this analysis simply by printing the result object.

result.mutex
## Pairwise DISCOVER mutual exclusivity test
## alternative hypothesis: observed overlap is less than expected by chance
## 
## number of pairs tested: 3403
## proportion of true null hypotheses: 0.928959
## number of significant pairs at a maximum FDR of 0.01 : 24

The print method for the pairwise.discover.out class optionally takes an argument with which the false discovery rate (FDR) threshold is selected. By default, a maximum FDR of 1% is used. Below, we get a summary of the test results using a somewhat more liberal threshold of 5%.

print(result.mutex, fdr.threshold=0.05) # Adjust the FDR threshold to 0.05 (default 0.01)
## Pairwise DISCOVER mutual exclusivity test
## alternative hypothesis: observed overlap is less than expected by chance
## 
## number of pairs tested: 3403
## proportion of true null hypotheses: 0.928959
## number of significant pairs at a maximum FDR of 0.05 : 80

It shows that the pairwise mutual exlusivity test was done over 3403 pairs of genes and with FDR threshold of 0.05 80 pairs look significant. Lets adjust the FDR threshold to 0.01 and see what happens.

print(result.mutex, fdr.threshold = 0.01)
## Pairwise DISCOVER mutual exclusivity test
## alternative hypothesis: observed overlap is less than expected by chance
## 
## number of pairs tested: 3403
## proportion of true null hypotheses: 0.928959
## number of significant pairs at a maximum FDR of 0.01 : 24

Because FDR is more strict in this case, less number of gene pairs are chosen as significant.

To get the pairs of genes which are significantly mutually exclusive, we can use the as.data.frame method. This method, too, takes an optional FDR threshold as argument. Below, we use the default of 1%.

as.data.frame(result.mutex)
##     gene1  gene2      p.value      q.value
## 5    TP53   CDH1 6.351270e-17 5.110740e-16
## 14   TP53  GATA3 5.470808e-15 3.138088e-14

4. Groupwise test

In the above results, we can identify a set of four genes- TP53, CDH1, GATA3, and MAP3K1 - for which all pairwise combinations are found mutually exclusive. We can use the groupwise.discover.test to assess whether this set of genes is also mutally exclusive as a group. This we can do by simply passing the subset of the discover.matrix that corresponds to the given genes.

genes <- c("TP53", "CDH1", "GATA3", "MAP3K1")
groupwise.discover.test(events[genes, ])
## Groupwise DISCOVER mutual exclusivity test
## 
## method: impurity
## P = 7.820036e-22

You can view the mutual exclusivity test results visualized as a plot.

plot(events[genes,])

Assort all significant genes (all genes) into a set and look into the result.

result_sig <- as.data.frame(result.mutex)
total_genes <- unique(c(result_sig$gene1, result_sig$gene2))
groupwise.discover.test(events[total_genes, ])
## Groupwise DISCOVER mutual exclusivity test
## 
## method: impurity
## P = 0.9999967
plot(events[total_genes, ])

III. Cancer Mutation Mutual Exclusivity & Coverage Analysis w/ CoMet: Programming Exclusivity and Coverage

1. Introduction to CoMet

CoMEt is an algorithm devised to identify combinations of alterations (mutations) that exhibit a pattern of mutual exclusivity across individuals, often observed in the same pathway. If you look at the figure above, you can see that blue sample set (M) is sampled so that it resembles what you can discover in a typical cancer genome study - where you have a small number of recurrently mutated genes and a long tail of rarely mutated genes. Set M (green) has better significance and thus has smaller value of \(\phi\), because it exhibits more frequency in each alteration and that raises the CoMEt score. On the right resides the \(2\times2\times2\) contingency table \(\rm{X}_M\) where you can see that \(\rm{m}_1\) and \(\rm{m}_2\) alteration status differs according to whether \(\rm{m}_3\) is altered or not. The full figure of CoMEt algorithm from the paper itself is placed below.

First, an alteration matrix is generated from biological data. Second, Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) algorithm is used to sample a collection of sets \(\rm{M}\), containing t sets of k alterations, in proportion to the weight \(\Phi(\rm{M}^{-\alpha})\). Here weve got sets M and M in a collection of two sets with three and two alterations respectively. Each collection is scored by \(\Phi(\textbf{M})=\prod^t_{i=1}\Phi(M_i)\) Identify all collections whose weight exceeds the maximum observed in randomly permuted datasets (a little bit like a permutation test? In the figure it is denoted as Identify significant collections, where such collections that have higher exclusivity score than maximum of randomly permuted real data). Then Marginal probability graph is built to represent the exclusion relationship among gene pairs, where each edge weights indicate the fraction of significant collections with the corresponding pair of alterations. After such graph is built, weak edges are weeded out so that only strongly mutual exclusive gene pairs are left. It seems that this algorithm has improved on MEMo(Mutual Exclusivity Modules) and Dendrix, perhaps? Not sure. Should look into this a bit more.

2. Practice

# Library Upload
library(cometExactTest)
# Mutation matrix (patient by gene)
bm_laml <- bm_laml[,-1] # delete a column at the very beginning where patient ID was present

Indexing can suppress one or several rows or columns using negative values. For example, x[-1,] will suppress the first row, whereas x[c(-1, -15),] will suppress the first and fifteenth rows. Same goes with above expression and bm_laml[,-1] suppresses the very first column (gene) of bm_laml from being sliced (cited from R for Beginners by Paradis p.27.) The first column contained patient (sample) ID info, so for a more convenient analysis its much better to exclude this column from the data frame.

# Set preparation (default value is 2)
set_size <-3
geneset_list<-combn(gene, set_size)

When combn(x, m, FUN = NULL, simplify = TRUE, ), combn function return all combinations of x taken m at a time. FUN designates a specific function where each point will pass through. simplify=TRUE means that the return value will be an array or a matrix, but if simplify=FALSE it will return a list.1

# Mutual exclusivity

result_ex <- matrix(ncol=5,nrow=ncol(geneset_list))
colnames(result_ex) <- c("g1", "g2", "g3", "ex_pval", "coverage")
for ( g in 1:ncol(geneset_list)){
  laml_ex <- bm_laml[,geneset_list[,g]]
  # Index that particular gene
  g1 <- geneset_list[,g][1] 
  g2 <- geneset_list[,g][2]
  g3 <- geneset_list[,g][3]
  # Put those gene set (of 3) into corresponding columns ("g1", "g2", "g3")
  result_ex[g, 1] <- g1
  result_ex[g, 2] <- g2
  result_ex[g, 3] <- g3
  mat <- table(laml_ex[,g3], laml_ex[,g1], laml_ex[,g2])
  mat <- as.vector(mat)
  
  # adjusted parameter setting (default=1)
  default <- 1
  mat <- mat+default
  
  # Give exclusive pattern graph drawing option, so
  # that it will generate the graph.
  # The graph will be saved in the current working directory.
  result_ex[g,4] <- comet_exact_test(mat, mutmatplot=TRUE)
  
  #coverage
  comp <- apply(laml_ex, 1, sum) #laml_ex row-wise sum (sample-wise)
  result_ex[g,5] <- round(length(comp[comp!=0])/length(comp), 2) 
  # Number of samples where any mutation exists (elements in comp where != 0) 
  # divided by the number of samples (total length of comp).
}

IV. Visualization of Cancer Genomic Mutations

Introduction to GISTIC (Genomic Identification of Significant Targets in Cancer)

Cancer analysis can be divided into two categories, broadly: SNV/INDEL level mutations and Chromosome/CNV level somatic copy number alteration(SCNA) or structural variation. Traditionally, SCNA analysis have been achieved with microarrays like SNP array or Array CGH (comparative genomic hybridization)2. Nowadays, CNV detection as well as SNV detection is possible through NGS data analysis. GISTIC is a method, algorithm, and software for analyzing CNV with NGS data. In this practice, we learn how to detect CNV and CNV-related mutual exclusivity pattern.

1. Load Somatic Mutation Profile

# TCGA somatic mutation profile is loaded.
laml.maf = system.file("extdata", "tcga_laml.maf.gz", package= "maftools")
laml =read.maf(maf = laml.maf, removeSilent = TRUE, useALL= FALSE)

Theres a slight error because of unused arguments. I searched it up, and it seems the arguments removeSilent and useALL are used in maftools v0.99.30. However, I have installed from BioConductor the latest version (2.2.10) of maftools package in R, as can be seen by applying packageVersion function. Instead, newer read.maf is as follows:

read.maf( maf, clinicalData = NULL, removeDuplicatedVariants = TRUE, useAll = TRUE, gisticAllLesionsFile = NULL, gisticAmpGenesFile = NULL, gisticDelGenesFile = NULL, gisticScoresFile = NULL, cnLevel = all, cnTable = NULL, isTCGA = FALSE, vc_nonSyn = NULL, verbose = TRUE )

packageVersion("maftools")
## [1] '2.2.10'

The maftools 2.2.10 documentation is at this link. The documentation states that you dont require any other argument (other than optional clinical data that contains survival information and histology) but only MAF file.

As you can see, we are required the clinical data here, but it is nowhere to be found because we havent assigned the data to any variable. We do the same procedure with other preset data in maftools directory under extdata. The file name is tcga_laml_annot.tsv.3

laml.clin <- system.file("extdata", "tcga_laml_annot.tsv", package = "maftools")

Now we try read.maf function, yet again, with clinicalData.

laml = read.maf(maf = laml.maf, clinicalData=laml.clin)
## -Reading
## -Validating
## -Silent variants: 475 
## -Summarizing
## -Processing clinical data
## -Finished in 0.179s elapsed (0.259s cpu)

laml.gistic = readGistic(gisticAllLesionsFile = all.lesions, gisticAmpGenesFile = amp.genes, gisticDelGenesFile = del.genes, gisticScoresFile = scores.gis, isTCGA=TRUE)

3. Visualization

Visualize the mutual exclusivity and mutation profile of the cancer genome and print it out as a graph.

Results

Basic Variant Graph

### Caution: If layout breaks, draw each graph separately and turn off R graphics device.

# Draw Out the Basic Variant Graph

plotmafSummary(maf = laml, rmOutlier = TRUE, addStat = 'median', dashboard = TRUE)

Chromosome-wide Copy Number Graph

gcp = gisticChromPlot(gistic = laml.gistic, markBands = "all")

Plot of Top 10 Mutated Genes

oncoplot(maf = laml.plus.gistic, top = 10, removeNonMutated = TRUE, sortByMutation = TRUE)

Selected Graph of Top 3 Mutated Genes

# Oncostrip sounds similar to oncoplot, but it sounds like it strips some data away.
oncostrip(maf = laml, genes = c('DNMT3A', 'NPM1', 'RUNX1'), removeNonMutated=TRUE, showTumorSampleBarcodes=FALSE)

Q: Why is RUNX1 chosen? I dont understand this part. It looks like that FLT3 must be included.

Ti/Tv ratio

# Ti/Tv ratio
laml.titv = titv(maf = laml, plot = FALSE, useSyn = TRUE)
# plot Ti/Tv summary
plotTiTv(res = laml.titv)
